      narrative: "Maya was 16 when she first started experimenting with substances at parties — small things at first, then quickly escalating. By 17 she was hiding a serious addiction from her family and attending church every Sunday as if nothing had changed. A youth leader noticed the distance in her eyes and, after months of careful relationship-building, Maya finally told the truth. The leader did not give her a programme or a rulebook. She gave her three pieces of paper, each with one verse: Deuteronomy 8:3, Deuteronomy 6:16, and Deuteronomy 6:13 — the three Scriptures Jesus used against Satan in the wilderness. Then Psalm 119:11: 'Thy word have I hid in mine heart, that I might not sin against thee.' 'Memorise these,' the leader said. 'Say them out loud when the craving comes. Jesus won the wilderness with these words. You can win with the same weapon.' Maya was sceptical — it seemed too simple. But she memorised them. And when the craving came — usually at 10pm, alone in her room — she would say them out loud. Not silently. Out loud. Like a declaration. Like a weapon. It took months. There were setbacks. But the Word, spoken aloud in the dark, gradually broke the pattern. Three years later, Maya leads the small group for girls in her youth ministry. Her opening exercise every term: helping every girl memorise those same four verses. 'If it worked for Jesus,' she tells them, 'it works for you.'",
