      narrative: "Park was a young seminary student in post-Korean War Seoul, convinced that real ministry meant preaching to educated people with theological questions. He had mastered the Sermon on the Mount academically — he could exegete every beatitude — and he was waiting for an important assignment. Instead, he was sent to a shantytown on the edge of the city: mud-floored huts, families living on almost nothing, most of them unable to read. He arrived resentful. He stayed out of obligation. One evening he was reading 'Blessed are they that mourn: for they shall be comforted' to a woman who had lost her husband and two children to the war. She was not educated. She did not know Greek. But when she heard those words, she grabbed his arm and said: 'Tell me more about this Jesus who knows about our mourning.' In that moment, Park understood something he had never understood in seminary. The Beatitudes were not academic theology for comfortable people. They were the words of a King spoken directly to the people who had nothing else. The poor in spirit, the mourning, the meek — these were not problems to be solved. They were the people Jesus described as blessed. He planted a church in that shantytown. It grew until it had to meet outdoors. He spent the rest of his ministry among the people the educated church had overlooked — because he had learned that the Sermon on the Mount is not a description of the comfortable life. It is a description of the Spirit-filled life. And the Spirit goes where the need is greatest.",
